textDisplay:
Currently there is no computer that is intelligent like a human. We‚Äôre still just mimicking aspects of intelligence, a term that has been defined downward so we could apply it to machines.

The human brain has over a trillion neural connections taking in data from at least 5 sensory inputs over a lifetime. How that data is processed, stored and synthesized is still difficult to replicate with current hardware and software.

Google‚Äôs Deep Mind beat Lee Sedol at the game of Go a few years back but required a team of engineers to operate and thousands of watts of electricity. Sedol can walk, jump, run, take the subway, climb stairs, sit in a chair, and even learn a new game. In contrast, Deep Mind is stationary, requires a fixed power source, has to be disassembled, and retrained to a specific task within it‚Äôs potential ability. This is not intelligence.

textDisplay:
I kinda object to the "blank slate baby" metaphor.
A baby isn't as empty as an AI is when you sit down and try to build it/build itself.
A baby has prewritten code in the genome. It's already primed to do certain tasks. It doesn't have to grow/invent a speech center, it already have a part of the brain that is predisposed to that functionality. The oldest "code" in the baby is as old as life itself. (sure I guess the code-remnants of single cell life won't help the baby play chess, but it's still there)

textDisplay: Well I‚Äôm not impressed with Jabriel. If I rate this video‚Äôs content, I‚Äôd say it is good, well-researched perhaps, and well-written, though the volume of information is rather low, where the attempts at humor take away from the limited time to offer the history on the subject. The time feels even slower with how slow Jabriel speaks. Less words per minute means less information that can be shared. And as a CS student, this is really basic stuff, so I probably won‚Äôt revisit this series, but I very much enjoyed the CS Crash Course. So to critique the main problem, it is Jabriel‚Äôs presentation. The art of rhetoric is one of the seven main liberal arts historically taught. The delivery must be just as powerful as the information. It is hard to believe Jabriel is being sincere and not just following a well-written and researched script. Sure, Carrie Ann for Crash Course Computer Science did the same thing, but I wasn‚Äôt doubting that she didn‚Äôt know the material that she was delivering, like she had mastered it. There are a few things Jabriel can look into to make a more powerful and believable delivery, like how to improve the voice and going to the gym to boost testosterone. This can take years to improve, but it can be done. I encourage Jabriel to continue, grow, and learn from his experience teaching here. But if you want be a present, you need to know who you are, your capabilities. Clearly, many people such as those who post many comments on social media do not consider these things. Wouldn‚Äôt everyone ironically agree?

textDisplay:
Good intro, this is gonna be a good series.


There's something that bugs me about AI to this day though... which is something that always happens one way or another, but in context I guess it's worth discussing.


You see, this thing we have working today shouldn't have been called Artificial Intelligence. It is being called like that because it's simpler, because marketing, because semantics loses to practicity, and a bunch of other stuff.


But the vast majority of what we really have working today is machine learning with a few very specific applications for artificial neural networks.


Intelligence is a very general, very broad concept in itself. But I'd argue that among traits that are often attributed to intelligence, the so called artificial intelligence hasn't gotten even half of the easier ones for an automated system to get just yet.


Logic, learning to a point, planning to a point, problem solving for very specific problems. That's about it. It leaves out creativity, critical reasoning, understanding, reasoning, emotional knowledge, and perhaps most important of all - self-awareness.


A huge part of the fears about AI stems from two distinct things about AI evolution. One is pretty clear and has to be addressed as soon as possible - the usage of AI by bad actors. So it's not about AI as an evil thing, it's about the power of the tool itself. Which is just the same fear of nuclear power. In the wrong hands, it could be employed to make peoples' lives miserable, if not outright end life altogether.
It's easy enough to understand how. A dictatorship that wants to control it's population could use all sorts of algorithms, neural networks, machine learning and so called AI related techniques to get the upper hand and give power and control to a central power. It is already being employed in this way. So we have to take action to stop it, lest we wanna conform to a life under oppressive control.
Likewise, AI could be employed to developed even more powerful weapons of mass destruction. Train an AI to run through millions of scenarios modifying a virus or tweaking a disease, there you go.


But there is another very distinct fear - about what happens when artificial intelligence algorithms becomes so sophisticated running in machines so powerful that they achieve something like self-awareness. This is the distant scenario fear and worry, also known as singularity. This is further into the future, but something that people are starting to worry right now. Some argue that we'd need something like general intelligence for something like that to happen, which seems almost unreachable right now. Some think we don't need to go that far.


In any case, a topic worth discussing. Glad to see CrashCourse covering it.

textDisplay:
You're jumping straight from the introduction to machine learning algorithms? Absolutely no mention of Ye Olde AI, like the kind that beat chess champions?
You say that babies receive millions of inputs to learn from, but it's really not that impressive. So much of the input is the same and a baby doesn't need to see thousands of apples to identify an apple. A baby who has seen ONE apple can better recognize another apple than an AI that has seen hundreds. This is a problem that needs to be solved in order for AI to even approach human levels. It's because of this problem that current techniques likely won't lead to general intelligence no matter how much power is put behind it.
